  "answer": "## Answer\nReAct-style agents and planner-executor agents differ mainly in **where planning lives**.\n\n- **ReAct** keeps reasoning and acting in the same loop: the model alternates between a thought/reasoning trace and a tool/action, then uses the observation to decide the next step. The original paper describes this as generating “reasoning traces and task-specific actions in an interleaved manner.” [ReAct paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629)\n- **Planner-executor** systems separate those roles: one component produces a plan, and another component executes subtasks and returns results for synthesis. LangGraph’s orchestrator-worker docs describe the orchestrator generating a plan, dispatching workers, and then synthesizing their outputs. [LangGraph docs](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langgraph/workflows-agents)\n\nPractical takeaway: **ReAct is more reactive and step-by-step**, which is good when the next move depends heavily on fresh observations; **planner-executor is more structured**, which is good when you want clearer decomposition, easier debugging, and potentially parallel execution of subtasks. That last sentence is a synthesis from the sources, not a direct quote. [LangChain agents docs](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/agents) [LangGraph docs](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langgraph/workflows-agents)\n\n## Sources\n- [ReAct: Synergizing Reasoning and Acting in Language Models](https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.03629)\n- [Workflows and agents - Docs by LangChain](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langgraph/workflows-agents)\n- [Agents - Docs by LangChain](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langchain/agents)\n\n## Limitations\nThis is a high-level comparison. \"Planner-executor\" is not one fixed algorithm, so some implementations may blur the line and include replanning, hierarchical planners, or multiple executors. I did not include benchmark numbers because the question asked for conceptual differences, not performance."
